06456nam a22009495i 9783110730388DE-B159720230228015514.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107303887 a10.1515/97831107303882doi  a(DE-B1597)573192  a(OCoLC)1298722876  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0041902bisacsh00aHistory of Classical Philology :bFrom Bentley to the 20th century /ced. by Gherardo Ugolini, Diego Lanza. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (X, 366 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Classics – Scholarship in the Making ,x2701-1100 ;v200tFrontmatter -- tPreface to the Current Edition -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Towards a Science of Antiquity -- tRichard Bentley and Philology as the Art of Conjecture -- tChristian Gottlob Heyne: New Ways of Studying Antiquity -- tFriedrich August Wolf and the Birth of the Altertumswissenschaft -- tHumboldt, the Classical Gymnasium, and the University of Berlin -- tPart II: The Illusion of the Archetype. Classical Studies in Nineteenth-Century Germany -- tKarl Lachmann: Method and Science -- tHermann contra Boeckh: Formal Philology and Historical Philology -- tNietzsche and the Controversy over the Tragic -- tWilamowitz: Philology as ‘Totality’ -- tPart III: Classical Philology in the Twentieth- Century -- tWerner Jaeger and the Third Humanism -- tGiorgio Pasquali and Philology as a Historical Science -- tNew Antiquities: The Papyri -- tRetelling Antiquity: Words and Images -- tPostwar Philology: New Perspectives -- tWorks of Classical Philology: A Select Bibliography -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex of Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn updated history of classical philology had long been a desideratum of scholars of the ancient world. The volume edited by Diego Lanza and Gherardo Ugolini is structured in three parts. In the first one (“Towards a science of antiquity”) the approach of Anglo-Saxon philology (R. Bentley) and the institutionalization of the discipline in the German academic world (C.G. Heyne and F.A. Wolf) are described. In the second part (“The illusion of the archetype. Classical Studies in the Germany of the 19th Century”) the theoretical contributions and main methodological disputes that followed are analysed (K. Lachmann, J.G. Hermann, A. Boeckh, F. Nietzsche and U. von Wilamowitz-Moellendorff). The last part (“The classical philology of the 20th century”) treats the redefinition of classical studies after the Great War in Germany (W. Jaeger) and in Italy (G. Pasquali). In this context, the contributions of papyrology and of the new images of antiquity that have emerged in the works of writers, narrators, and translators of our time have been considered. This part finishes with the presentation of some of the most influential scholars of the last decades (B. Snell, E.R. Dodds, J.-P. Vernant, B. Gentili, N. Loraux).  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aClassical philologyy20th century. 4aBoeckh. 4aNietzsche. 4aWilamowitz. 4aWolf. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aBoeckh.  aNietzsche.  aWilamowitz.  aWolf.1 aBossina, Luciano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFornaro, Sotera, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLanza, Diego, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLanza, Diego, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLettieri, Antonella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLupi, Francesco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPinto